Problem Brief: Mator wants to start a used car resale business but does not understand how to set prices for cars. Armed with an incomplete dataset about used car sales, they would like our expertise to predict whether a used car price should be high or low.

Objective: Our objective is to create a model that will enable them to predict the (high or low) prices of the used cars. We will do this by creating two separate models (logistic regression and decision tree) and then compare them to see which is more reliable and accurate.

Data Description: The data we were given was a set of information on new and used cars sold previously. For each sold car, it gave key variables such as year, make, model, color, mileage, owner count, certified pre-owned, and price. The set also had other useful data related to the individual cars. we used the variables that we thought would have the biggest impact on the price while also allowing our models to be efficeint and accurate.

Data Transformations: For data transformation, we took out all of the variables that were not needed for the model, and then factorized all of the categorical variables. We then cleaned the data by removing empty strings with the complete.cases function. After this, the data was ready to be used to train our models.

Pre-processing: To start our models, we reordered our variables to only use the ones that we thought would be important for our model to accurately and efficiently predict prices. Originally, we were using more variables, but some of them slowed down the model and made is very inefficient, without much improvement to accuracy. Next, we factorized the categorical variables and renamed the outcomes from 0 and 1 to Low and High. We then made sure to clean the data to get rid of any empty strings, and then split the data for training and validation.

1- Logistic Regression: This model preformed fairly well in training with and accuracy of .862, sensitivity of .585, specificity of .952, F1 score of .676 and AUC of .769. From these numbers, we can tell that through training, the model is good at predicting the low prices with a high specificity, but is not as good at predicting the high prices with a sensitivity of .585. The F1 score tells us the balance of precision and sensitivity, and .676 is a good value for the training set. The AUC or area under the curve tells us how good the model is at distinguishing between the TPR and TNR. The closer to 1 a value is, the better it is at distinguishing which makes .769 a fair value for the model. For the validation set, it also preformed well with an accuracy of .861, sensitivity of .589, specificity of .947, F1 score of .6702, and AUC of .768. Compared to the training set, these values are very good. The validation set preformed almost the exact same as the training set with minor variance in the values. This means that there was no over-fitting and luck involved in the validation model. This model is very consistent with its training and is fairly good at predicting what it is supposed to. With the new data, the model made predictions with the probablities being far away from .5 in either direction. This means that the model was super confident in its decision on predicting a car to be at a high or low cost.

For the new data, we can see the predictions and the probability calculated by the model. The probability value tells us how likely the car is to have a high price. Anything below .5 will mean it is a low price, and anything above .5 means that it is more likely to have a high price. This is because we set the positive value to be high in the beginning. For the first two cars, the probability of it being a high price is .012 and .0056. These are very low, and therefore most likely to be low prices. The next two cars have a .828 and .589 probability of being a high price, which means that they will mostly likely have a high price. Although they are both predicted to have a high price, car 3 is more likely to have a high price as it is closer to 1. The last car has a .0034 probability of being a high price, which means that it will most likely have a lower price. The probabilities predicted by the model for the most part are far away from .5 in either direction which means that the model is making confident predictions. The closer it is to .5, the more uncertain the prediction is.

2- Decision Tree: The model of the decision tree also performed quite well, with an accuracy of 0.856, sensitivity of 0.531(not as good), specificity of 0.965, an AUC of 0.744, and an F1 score of 0.650. Like the previous model, the training proves that the model is good at predicting actual low prices, but is not good at predicting the possibilities of higher prices with a sensitivity that is barely over 50 percent. The F1 score score, showing tghe balance of precision and sensitivity is a decent value for the training set. The area under the curve, measuring performance with TPR and TNR, with a value of 0.74 is q good value for the model. The validation set had an accuracy of 0.854, sensitivity of 0.514, specificity of 0.966, F1 score of 0.635, and an AUC of 0.74. The validation set performed extremely similarly, with only minor decreases in each of the values, meaning that there is no luck or overfitting in the model itself. It is very consistent with its training and is fairly good at predicting what it is supposed to.

Chosen Model: The model that we decided to choose was the logistic regression model. Overall, it had a bit more accuracy and was better at distinguishing between the TPR and TNR with a higher AUC. It also preformed well with the new data, as it gave confident predictions with the probabilities being far away from .5 in either direction. The model was also overall cleaner which would make it eaiser for the client to look at and use. The decision tree models labels were small and bunched up and a little difficult to read at times. library(rpart.plot)
library(caret)
names(train_df)
## [1] "body_type"      "franchise_make" "is_cpo"         "mileage"       
## [5] "owner_count"    "year"           "price_nom"
class_tr <- rpart(price_nom ~ body_type + franchise_make + is_cpo + mileage + owner_count + year,
                  data = train_df, method = "class",
                  maxdepth = 30)
prp(class_tr, cex = 0.8, tweak = 1)

class_tr_v2 <- rpart(price_nom ~ body_type + franchise_make + is_cpo + mileage + owner_count + year,
                  data = train_df, method = "class", minbucket = 2,
                  maxdepth = 15)
prp(class_tr_v2, cex = 0.8, tweak = 1)

rpart.plot(class_tr_v2, type = 4)

printcp(class_tr)
## 
## Classification tree:
## rpart(formula = price_nom ~ body_type + franchise_make + is_cpo + 
##     mileage + owner_count + year, data = train_df, method = "class",

## 3 0.035076      4   0.64302 0.64788 0.0102658
## 4 0.010000      6   0.57287 0.58142 0.0098217
class_tr_cp <- rpart(price_nom ~ body_type + franchise_make + is_cpo + mileage + owner_count + year,
                  data = train_df, method = "class",
                  maxdepth = 30, cp = 0.01000)
prp(class_tr_cp, cex = 0.8, tweak = 1)

rpart.plot(class_tr_cp, type = 4)

#confusion matrix for training set

# first training the prediction
class_tr_train_predict <- predict(class_tr, train_df,
                                  type = "class")

t(t(head(class_tr_train_predict,10)))

#f1 score for training
con_mat_train_1 <- confusionMatrix(class_tr_train_predict, train_df$price_nom, 
                                 positive = "High")

sensitivity_train <- con_mat_train_1$byClass[1]

precision_train <- con_mat_train_1$byClass[3]
f1_train <- 2/((1/sensitivity_train) + (1/precision_train))

# Use this to avoid awkward naming. It's just the way it works.
# f1_train <- unname(f1_train)

paste("The F1 score for training is", f1_train)
## [1] "The F1 score for training is 0.650130548302872"
ROSE::roc.curve(train_df$price_nom, class_tr_train_predict)

## Area under the curve (AUC): 0.748
